&gt; &gt; &gt;  On Tue, 6 Jul 2004, hedgi wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   Now I there is the problem. I want to run &quot;testCommon&quot; first
&gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   which is in the &quot;BasicGetListTest&quot; but when I subclass it with
&gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   &quot;GlucoseGetListTest&quot; it is always executed last. I read some of
&gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   the postings in this newsgroup, but it seems that such kind of
&gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   requirement point a desing flaw and I should somehow rearrange my
&gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   Unit Test Structure to made the tests indepentdant. I&#39;m stuck
with
&gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   it.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;  I&#39;ve been thinking for a while that this is a serious problem in
JUnit
&gt; &gt; &gt;  (and most unit testing frameworks), because it&#39;s been such an
annoyance
&gt; &gt; &gt;  for so many people. Let&#39;s face it; a lot of groups of tests do have
&gt; &gt; &gt;  known dependencies between tests such that if test A fails, we know
&gt; that
&gt; &gt; &gt;  the output of tests B, C and D are uninteresting. Yet we end up
running
&gt; &gt; &gt;  B, C and D anyway, and then searching through all the error output
for
&gt; &gt; &gt;  the failure that we know is the &quot;real&quot; one, ignoring all the others
as
&gt; &gt; &gt;  spurious.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; With all due respect, I believe that is a code smell.  It seems to say
to
&gt; me
&gt; &gt; that there is something not right about the design of the code being
&gt; tested,
&gt; &gt; or perhaps even more elusive, something is wrong with how the tests are
&gt; &gt; written.  When I find these types of dependencies I inevitably rethink
how
&gt; I
&gt; &gt; have written my tests.  Have I coded in the dependencies or are they
&gt; really
&gt; &gt; there.  More times than not I have coded in the dependencies -- and
&gt; therefore
&gt; &gt; I can remove them.  Further, I would argue that I _NEED_ to remove them.
&gt; &gt; Now, maybe I am old-fashioned but I believe tests (at least at the
&gt; &gt; unit/programmer level) ought to be as autonomous as possible.
&gt; &gt;
